abstract.value: Sheila Lukins (1942- 2009) was a food writer, cookbook author, grocery-store owner, and caterer. She was a co-author of <emph render="italic">The Silver Palate Cookbook</emph>, and later became the food editor of <emph render="italic">Parade</emph> magazine, succeeding Julia Child in the position and contributing to her column there, "Simply Delicious." The Sheila Lukins Papers include drafts of recipes for <emph render="italic">Parade</emph> magazine; notebooks containing writing on foods from the United States and around the world; correspondence; publicity and press clippings for Lukins, her store, and her cookbooks; issues of <emph render="italic">Parade</emph> magazine and other magazines; CD-ROMs; and videocassettes.

p.value: Materials are open to researchers. Please contact the Fales Library and Special Collections, fales.library@nyu.edu, 212-998-2596.

Identification of item,  date (if known); Sheila Lukins Papers; MSS 281; box number; folder number; Fales Library and Special Collections, New York University Libraries.

Sheila Lukins (1942- 2009) was a food writer, cookbook author, grocer, and caterer. Born in Philadelphia, PA, and raised in Norwalk and Westport, CT, Lukins attended Tyler School of Fine Arts and the School of Visual Arts,  and received a bachelor's in Art Education from the New York University in 1970. After graduating, Lukins moved to London with her husband, Richard Lukins, where she attended Le Cordon Bleu. On returning to New York in 1972, Lukins began the Other Woman Catering Company out of her apartment at the Dakota, at Central Park West and 72nd Street. In 1977, she opened the Silver Palate gourmet grocery with partner Julee Russo on the Upper West Side.<lb/><lb/>With Russo, Lukins coauthored <emph render="italic">The Silver Palate Cookbook,</emph> in 1982, which has since sold more than two and a half million copies. Lukins went on to author other bestselling cookbooks, such as <emph render="italic">The Silver Palate Cookbook, The Silver Palate Good Times Cookbook, U.S.A. Cookbook, The New Basics Cookbook, Celebrate!</emph> and <emph render="italic">All Around the World Cookbook</emph>.<lb/><lb/>In 1986, Lukins became the food editor of <emph render="italic">Parade</emph> magazine, succeeding Julia Childs in the position, and contributing to her column there, "Simply Delicious".<lb/><lb/>In 1988, The Silver Palate was sold to investors and eventually closed, in 1993. Lukins won many awards as a small-business owner and a cookbook author and was a member of Les Dames d'Escoffier, the American Institute of Wine and Food, the James Beard Foundation, and the International Association of Cooking Professionals.<lb/>

Series I: Professional Files1976-2007Scope and Content

Series comprises material relating to Sheila Lukins role as food writer, cookbook author, and proprietor of the Silver Palate. Materials include correspondence; recipes; drafts for food columns at Parade; correspondence, publicity, and other materials related to her cookbooks; press and clippings for Lukins, her cookbooks, or the Silver Palate.

Arrangement

Subseries A, C, D, E, and G are arranged chronologically. Undated material is filed at the end of the series in alphabetical order by folder label.Subseries B and F are arranged alphabetically by folder label.

Series comprises photographs taken of and by Sheila Lukins. Most photographs concern travel across the United States and abroad for food-related events and research (though the photographs appear to be a mix of personal vacation photos and photographs of food, food vendors, and food-related events). A few photographs are publicity shots for the Silver Palate grocery and The Silver Palate Cookbook.

Arrangement

Eight photograph binders that were originally labeled #1 through #8 appear in numerical order. Unnumbered binders are ordered alphabetically, with unlabeled binders at the end. Photographic sleeves that were too large for binders are placed in folders corresponding to their binder and ordered alphabetically by their original binder's label.
